  { question: "What is a MAC address?", answer: "A MAC (Media Access Control) address is a unique 48-bit identifier assigned to a network interface controller (NIC) for use at the data link layer (Layer 2) of the OSI model. It is typically written as six pairs of hexadecimal digits separated by colons or hyphens, such as AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF. Every Ethernet, Wi-Fi, and Bluetooth adapter has a MAC address, which is used for communication within a local network segment. Unlike IP addresses that can change, MAC addresses are typically burned into the hardware by the manufacturer." },
  { question: "What is an OUI prefix?", answer: "The OUI (Organizationally Unique Identifier) is the first three bytes (24 bits) of a MAC address. The IEEE (Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers) assigns OUI prefixes to manufacturers and organizations. By looking up the OUI prefix, you can determine which company manufactured the network interface. For example, the OUI prefix 00:50:56 belongs to VMware, and AC:DE:48 belongs to Apple. The IEEE maintains the authoritative OUI registry." },
  { question: "What is the difference between unicast and multicast MAC addresses?", answer: "The least significant bit (bit 0) of the first byte of a MAC address determines whether it is unicast or multicast. If this bit is 0, the address is unicast, meaning it identifies a single specific network interface. If the bit is 1, the address is multicast, meaning frames sent to this address are received by multiple interfaces configured to listen for that multicast group. The broadcast address FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF is a special case of multicast that reaches all devices on the local network." },
  { question: "What does globally unique vs locally administered mean?", answer: "The second least significant bit (bit 1) of the first byte indicates whether a MAC address is globally unique (UAA - Universally Administered Address) or locally administered (LAA). If this bit is 0, the address was assigned by the manufacturer and should be globally unique. If the bit is 1, the address was set by software or an administrator and may not be unique beyond the local network. Virtual machines, Docker containers, and MAC randomization features use locally administered addresses." },
  { question: "What is MAC address randomization?", answer: "MAC address randomization is a privacy feature implemented by iOS (since iOS 8), Android (since Android 10), and Windows (since Windows 10). When scanning for Wi-Fi networks, devices generate random locally administered MAC addresses instead of using their real hardware address. This prevents tracking by retailers, advertisers, and network operators who could otherwise identify and follow devices by their fixed MAC addresses. Some operating systems also randomize the MAC address on a per-network basis when connecting." }
